<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,1522,2028]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1522,1548]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A member of the 
<taxonomicName box="[518,807,1523,1548]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis box="[518,807,1523,1548]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Leptotyphlops nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group, distinguished from neighbouring 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="emini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">L. emini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its relatively higher middorsal counts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,1522,2028]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,1602,1628]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Description.</emphasis>
Body cylindrical, with head and neck broadened and flattened, the short tail tapers slightly before a short stout spine or a blunt tail cone.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,1522,2028]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Snout rounded, rostral broad (0.43–0.45 head width, mean = 0.44) and truncated posteriorly, much wider than supranasals dorsally and extending to a line connecting centre of eyes, a preoral groove present ventrally. Behind rostral, upper lip bordered by infranasal (nostril nearer rostral than supralabial along nasal suture), small anterior supralabial that reaches level of nostril with a width along lip 2.0–3.0 times that of the infranasal, large ocular with eye central in upper half, and tall posterior supralabial. Supraoculars pentagonal, slightly larger than the hexagonal frontal and postfrontal, which are slightly smaller than the interparietal and interoccipital. Parietals oblique, subequal to the fused occipitals, in contact with the posterior supralabials. Temporal single.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,1522,2028]" lastBlockId="35.[151,1248,152,298]" lastPageId="35" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Body covered with 14 rows of smooth, imbricate, subequal scales. Reduction to 10 rows on the tail takes place lateral to the subtriangular cloacal shield. Total middorsals 204–247; subcaudals 21–31.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1248,152,298]" box="[198,963,192,218]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Total length/diameter ratio 44–77; total length/tail ratio 8.0–13.5.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1248,152,298]" box="[198,796,232,258]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Uniformly dark brown to black dorsum and venter.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1248,152,298]" box="[198,1133,272,298]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Skull with fused parietal bones as in 
<taxonomicName box="[630,914,272,297]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis box="[630,914,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Leptotyphlops nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[929,1014,272,298]" captionStart="PLATE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,238,1626,1650]" captionTargetBox="[307,1289,197,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-257@11.[263,1331,162,1634]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="PLATE 4. Figure 1. Dorsal views of the skulls of Leptotyphlops. A. Leptotyphlops nigricans (MCZ 21473) and B. Leptotyphlops kafubi (FMNH 56374), both after List (1966). KEY to bone abbreviations from List, 1966: Ax = axis, At = atlas, Eo = exoccipital, F = frontal, M = maxilla, N = nasal, P = parietal, Pf = prefrontal, Po = prootic, So = supraoccipital. C. Leptotyphlops cairi, after Abdeen et al. (1991). KEY to bone abbreviations from Abdeen et al., 1991: B.OC. = basioccipital; B.SP. = basisphenoid; C.T.C. = cartilaginouis trebacula cranii; EX.OC. = exoccipital; FR. = frontal; L.P.P.MX. = lateral process of maxilla; MX. = maxilla; NA. = nasal; OC.CO. = occipital condyle; P.MX. = premaxilla; P.OT. = prootic; P.VO. = prevomer; PA. = palatine; PR. = parietal; PR.FR. = prefrontal; PR.L.DG. = lateral downgrowth of parietal; PT. = pterygoid; S.OC. = supraoccipital. The lines represent 1 mm to scale. The stipple indicates thin transparent membrane. Figure 2. Dorsal views of the skulls of Leptotyphlops. A. Leptotyphlops nigroterminus sp. nov. (ZMB 51610); B. Leptotyphlops macrurus (BMNH 1957.1.10.26); C. Leptotyphlops boulengeri (MCZ 40087); D. Leptotyphlops reticulatus (BMNH 1954.1.12.77). E. Leptotyphlops longicaudus (NMZB-UM 29371); F. Leptotyphlops blanfordii (BMNH 1977.833); G. Leptotyphlops nursii (FMNH 66158). H. Leptotyphlops scutifrons merkeri (NMZB 8089). The lines represent 1 mm to scale. KEY: f = frontal; n = nasal; p = parietal; pp = postparietal; so = supraoccipital." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6789072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6789072/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Plate 4</figureCitation>
, Fig. 1A).
</paragraph>
